{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3a1b5356-6cde-473b-81cb-7aeab731d654","content":"Analyzing .dmp files is outside the scope of the tools I have available here, but here's a quick guide:\n\n**Options for analyzing your dump:**\n\n1. **`dotnet-dump analyze`** (cross-platform):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet tool install -g dotnet-dump\n   dotnet-dump analyze your-file.dmp\n   ```\n   Useful commands inside: `clrstack`, `pe` (print exception), `dumpheap`, `threads`.\n\n2. **Visual Studio** (Windows): File → Open → File → select the `.dmp` → click \"Debug with Managed Only.\"\n\n3. **lldb + SOS** (Linux/macOS):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet-sos install\n   lldb --core your-file.dmp\n   ```\n\n**Typical first steps:**\n- Run `pe` to print the last exception\n- Run `threads` then `setthread <id>` + `clrstack` to inspect call stacks\n- Run `dumpheap -stat` to check for memory issues\n\nWould you like help setting up **dump collection** for future crashes instead?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"43f3738c-351e-4ca7-b83d-adf4d0c79389","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about analyzing a .dmp crash dump file. Let me check the available skills - there's a `dump-collect` skill, but its description specifically says:\n\n- USE FOR: enabling automatic crash dumps, capturing dumps, setting up dump collection\n- DO NOT USE FOR: analyzing or debugging dumps, post-mortem investigation with lldb/windbg/dotnet-dump analyze\n\nSo the dump-collect skill is NOT appropriate here. The user wants to analyze an existing dump, not collect one.\n\nLet me provide guidance on analyzing crash dumps myself.","outputTokens":398,"requestId":"6804:34CA9:AA319B1:B976D1A:69FD42F7"},"id":"1b78dd37-8826-4443-8f95-9fad3e8a84c6","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:57:23.703Z","parentId":"7a708f5f-72eb-4e7a-8a15-f820773f772b"}
